Cebu Air, Daewoo, MISC, Platinum, Samsung: Asia Ex-Japan Equities Preview

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-08-18T21:49:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-18/cebu-air-daewoo-misc-platinum-samsung-asia-ex-japan-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Cebu Air Inc. (CEB)  : The largest Philippine budget
carrier’s profit may decline again this quarter and next at a
“diminishing rate” as oil prices drop and the peso strengthens,
President Lance Gokongwei said. Cebu Air’s first-half profit
fell 23 percent. The stock was unchanged at 79.95 pesos.  Daewoo Engineering & Construction Co. (047040 KS): The
South Korean builder said it received an order to build a power
plant from Oman Power & Water Procurement Co. for $1.24 billion.
Construction will be completed by April 1, 2014, the Seoul-based
company said in an e-mailed statement. The stock fell 3.4
percent to 10,050 won.  First Philippine Holdings Corp. (FPH)  : The company
bought back 500,000 shares at 57.90 pesos each in the open
market, a stock-exchange filing showed. The stock was unchanged
at 58 pesos.  Lotte Shopping Co. (023530 KS): The South Korean department
store owner said second-quarter net income increased 17 percent
to 301.1 billion won ($280 million) in the three months ended
June 30, from a restated 257.1 billion won a year earlier on
earnings from  discount stores  and units including Lotte Card Co.
The stock climbed 2.1 percent to 485,000 won.  MISC Bhd. (MISC)  : The world’s biggest owner-operator of
liquefied natural gas tankers said net income in the first
quarter ended June 30 dropped 72 percent to 121.1 million
ringgit ($41 million) as its petroleum business incurred losses
from lower freight rates. MISC also has higher losses in its
liner business, it said in a statement. The stock rose 2.8
percent to 7.30 ringgit.  Platinum Asset Management Ltd. (PTM)  : The Australian
fund management company reported full-year net income of A$150.1
million ($157 million), according to a regulatory filing.
Analysts had forecast annual profit of A$147 million. The stock
fell 0.8 percent to A$3.69.  Samsung Electronics Co. (005930 KS):  Asia ’s biggest maker
of chips is close to buying U.S. software venture mSpot Inc.,
the Maeil Business Newspaper reported, without citing anyone.
The stock sank 5.7 percent to 709,000 won.  SM Prime Holdings Inc. (SMPH)  : The largest Philippine
shopping mall operator’s stock rating was raised to “buy” from
“hold” with a 12-month price target at 13.90 pesos a share by
Carl Sy, an analyst at Deutsche Bank AG. The stock increased 2.4
percent to 11.98 pesos.  Tradewinds Plantations Bhd. (TWPB MK): The Malaysian palm-
oil producer’s second-quarter profit more than tripled from a
year earlier to 90.1 million ringgit, according to a company
statement. The stock gained 6.1 percent to 3.49 ringgit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
